        <H2>
            Reduced Polynomial Degree
        </H2>

   A polynomial of degree $d$ in <a href="bform.html">Bernstein
   B&eacute;zier form </a>  
<P>
<IMG SRC = "e3.gif">
<p> may of course actually be of a degree less than $d$.  When it is
that fact is not readily apparent in the B-form.  However, the MDS
code described on these pages allows for the imposition of additional
conditions on the coefficients of <em>p</em> that force it to be of a
lesser degree than <em>d</em>.  These conditions are derived and
illustrated on this
page.

<p> A polynomial of degree <em>d</em> will be of degree <em>d-1</em> if <em>d+1</em>
independent derivatives of order <em>d</em> vanish.  Similar
conditions can be obtained to force <em>p</em> of degree even less
than <em>d-1</em>.  For simplicity we only described the conditions
used to obtain the degree <em>d-1</em>.

<p> The MDS code forces <em>p</em> to satisfy the conditions
